/PG436/XX/PR

/ITOn Festivals occurring on weekdays, substitute the following:/XX/PR

/PR

The world belongs to /SCG/XXOD/XX in all its fullness,/PR

the earth, and all who dwell on it,/PR

for God has founded it upon the waters,/PR

on the torrents, God established it./PR

Who can ascend the mount of /SCT/XXHE /XXE/XXTERNAL/XX?/PR

Who rises to the holy place of God?/PR

The one whose hands are clean, whose heart is pure,/PR

whose soul has not been vainly self-excusing,/PR

the one who never swore deceitfully./PR

/PR

That person reaps a blessing from /SCT/XXHE /XXA/XXLL-/XXK/XXNOWING /XXO/XXNE/XX,/PR

justice from the God of help./PR

For many generations now,/PR

the family of Jacob has sought your presence./PR

You city gates, open your bolts,/PR

eternal gates, be lifted up,/PR

and let the sovereign of glory come!/PI/PR

/ITWhose soul has not been vainly self-excusing/XX. Literally, "who has not lifted up
the soul in vain." The psalm turns on repetitions of the key verb, "lift up"
playing on its many meanings. Compare: "That person reaps [literally, lifts
up] a blessing...You city gates, open [literally, lift up] your gates, etc." The
pilgrim, ascending the steep slopes toward the Temple Mount, contem-
plates, through this interplay of associations, the fundamental act of pil-
grimage: an offering-up to God.    /SC/XXJ.R./XX/PR

/PR

/SCN/XXOTE/XX. This psalm asks and answers several questions, suggesting that it
was sung antiphonally in ancient times with the congregation singing the
responses.    /SC/XXD.A.T./XX/PR

