/SCN/XXOTE/XX. Traditional siddurim place an additional (/ITMusaf/XX) /ITAmidah/XX after returning the Torah to the ark. The /ITMusaf Amidah/XX corresponds to the additional sacrifice that was offered in the Temple on Shabbat and Festivals. Because Reconstructionists do not anticipate or hope for the rebuilding of the Temple, we do not feel a strong need to retain its liturgical rhythms or emphasis on animal sacrifice. This siddur therefore omits the /ITMusaf Amidah/XX for the sake of brevity. /ITYismeh/±u/XX, a joyfully sung part of the /ITMusaf Amidah/XX, is included in the /ITShah/±arit Amidah/XX here (page 309). For a shortened form of /ITMusaf/XX, some communities chant /ITMagen Avot/XX (page 111), often including the /ITMusaf Kedushah/XX, which this siddur incorporates into the Festival /ITShah/±arit Amidah/XX, pages 336-339 (omitting the two lines beginning /ITadir adirenu/XX, page 339). Many congregations recite poetry in the place of the /ITMusaf Amidah/XX as well. Those wishing to recite a full /ITMusaf Amidah/XX may use the separate booklet prepared for that purpose or turn back to the Shabbat /ITAmidah/XX found on pages 294-323, omitting page 307 or replacing it with a reading from pages 734-739. On Festivals, the Festival /ITAmidah/XX on pages 326-353 can be repeated for /ITMusaf/XX. If this is done, the /ITKedushah/XX on pages 302-305 should be used during /ITShah/±arit/XX, and the /ITKedushah/XX on pages 336-339 should be used during /ITMusaf/XX./PR

